\p
\v 8 When you didn'tÂŠ126979 know \nd GodÂŠ126981\nd*, you servedÂŠ126982 others who aren'tÂŠ126979 really godsÂŠ126988 at all.
\v 9 ButÂŠ126994 now that you do know God, or ratherÂŠ126993 now that God knows you, why would you turn back again to useless and inferior beliefs, to serve them all over again?
\v 10 You \add people\add* observeÂŠ127015 \add special\add* holidays and \add certain\add* monthsÂŠ127018 and seasonsÂŠ127020 and yearsÂŠ127022.
\v 11 I worry that maybe I'veÂŠ127028 wasted my time helping you.
\p
\v 12 I implore you to becomeÂŠ127032 like me, brothersÂŠ127039 andÂŠ127039 sistersÂŠ127039, becauseÂŠ127035 I'm also just like you. You haven't wrongedÂŠ127044 me in any way,
\v 13 but you know that it was a result of my fleshlyÂŠ127051 weakness that I originally preachedÂŠ127052 the goodÂŠ127052 messageÂŠ127052 to you.\f + \fr 4:13 \ft Scholars are unclear whether this might mean something like ill health, poor eyesight (see v15), or even a moral weakness, so we've left it as ambiguous in the translation as it is in the original.\f*
\v 14 Yet you didn'tÂŠ127066 mock or despise me, \add brothers andÂŠ127056 sisters,\add* for this trialÂŠ127058 of myÂŠ127065 fleshÂŠ127064, butÂŠ127056 rather you received me as God's messengerÂŠ127072 like you might have received the \nd messiahÂŠ127077 Yeshua\nd* himself.
